Great—this is actually one of the most underrated but highly used patterns in real-world backend systems. I’ll simplify it so you can recognize + explain + implement instantly in interviews.

🧠 1️⃣ What Template Method REALLY is

👉 One-line definition:

Template Method defines a fixed workflow (algorithm steps) but allows subclasses to customize individual steps.
🎯 Core Idea (VERY IMPORTANT)
Same process → Same steps → Same order  
But → Different implementations per step
🔥 2️⃣ Your Payment Example (Best Intuition)
Common Flow (FIXED)
1. Validate  
2. Debit  
3. Calculate Fees  
4. Credit

👉 This order must NEVER change

Variation
Step	Pay Friend	Pay Merchant
Validate	basic	stricter
Fees	0%	2%
Credit	full	minus fee

👉 So:

Structure SAME ✅  
Behavior DIFFERENT ✅
🧩 3️⃣ How Template Method Solves It
Step 1: Abstract Class (Template Owner)
abstract class PaymentFlow {

    // TEMPLATE METHOD (final)
    public final void sendMoney() {
        validate();
        debit();
        calculateFees();
        credit();
    }

    abstract void validate();
    abstract void debit();
    abstract void calculateFees();
    abstract void credit();
}
Step 2: Concrete Classes
💸 Pay to Friend
class PayToFriend extends PaymentFlow {

    void validate() {
        System.out.println("Basic validation");
    }

    void debit() {
        System.out.println("Debit full amount");
    }

    void calculateFees() {
        System.out.println("No fees");
    }

    void credit() {
        System.out.println("Credit full amount");
    }
}
🛒 Pay to Merchant
class PayToMerchant extends PaymentFlow {

    void validate() {
        System.out.println("Strict validation");
    }

    void debit() {
        System.out.println("Debit amount");
    }

    void calculateFees() {
        System.out.println("Apply 2% fee");
    }

    void credit() {
        System.out.println("Credit after fee deduction");
    }
}
Step 3: Client
PaymentFlow payment = new PayToMerchant();
payment.sendMoney();
⚡ 4️⃣ Key Design Points (INTERVIEW GOLD)
✅ 1. Template Method = final
Child classes cannot change flow ❌

👉 Guarantees order

✅ 2. Steps = abstract
Child classes customize behavior ✅
✅ 3. Control stays in parent
Parent = algorithm  
Child = implementation
🧠 5️⃣ When to Use (VERY IMPORTANT)

Use Template Method when:

✔ Same workflow across multiple classes
✔ Steps order must be fixed
✔ Some steps vary per class
✔ Want to avoid code duplication
🚨 6️⃣ Interview Trigger Words

If interviewer says:

“Same process but different implementations”
“Steps must follow same order”
“Enforce workflow structure”

👉 Your brain:

TEMPLATE METHOD ⚡
🔥 7️⃣ Real-World Examples
💳 Payment systems (your example)
🧾 Order processing
validate → process → invoice → notify
📦 Spring Framework (VERY COMMON)

JdbcTemplate

RestTemplate

👉 They define flow, you override parts

🧪 Testing frameworks

@Before → Test → @After

🆚 8️⃣ Template vs Strategy (VERY IMPORTANT)
Template Method
Inheritance-based  
Flow is FIXED  
Steps overridden
Strategy Pattern
Composition-based  
Algorithm is interchangeable  
Flow NOT fixed
🔥 Simple Difference
Pattern	Controls Flow
Template	Parent class
Strategy	Client
🧠 9️⃣ Memory Trick
Template = “Recipe”

👉 Recipe fixed:

Step 1 → Step 2 → Step 3

👉 But cooking style differs

⚡ 10️⃣ Common Mistake

❌ Letting child override full method

@Override
sendMoney() ❌

👉 Breaks pattern

✔ Always:

final sendMoney() ✅
🎯 11️⃣ Perfect Interview Answer
Template Method is a behavioral design pattern where a base class defines the skeleton of an algorithm, and subclasses override specific steps without changing the overall flow.
🚀 12️⃣ Deep Insight (Senior-Level)

👉 Why companies love this:

Consistency + Flexibility

Enforces business rules ✅

Allows customization ✅

Prevents bugs from wrong flow ❌

🔥 Final Understanding
Without Template:
Each class → random flow ❌

With Template:
Parent controls flow → children plug logic ✅